<!-- ══ KEY FINDINGS ══ -->
<div class="sec-head"><span class="sec-num">§04</span> Key Research Findings</div>
<div class="findings-grid">

  <div class="finding animate">
    <div class="finding-num">1</div>
    <div class="finding-title">English Has 2.6× More Hasty Generalizations</div>
    <div class="finding-body">German corpus: 26% prevalence. English corpus: 68%. This is not a language effect — it is a topic and argumentation culture effect. English speakers in this corpus argued more anecdotally, relying on personal examples rather than systemic claims. The biggest gap is in Crypto and AI topics.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">DE: 26% · EN: 68% — Δ +42 percentage points</div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding animate" style="animation-delay:.1s">
    <div class="finding-num">2</div>
    <div class="finding-title">Survivorship Bias is Primarily an English-Corpus Phenomenon</div>
    <div class="finding-body">Survivorship bias appeared in 12% of English arguments — but almost absent in German corpus. Concentrated in crypto (investors, entrepreneurs), AI (developers), and tech (engineers). These are domains where success stories are more visible than failures. System now flags this for technology sector arguments.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">EN: 12% survivorship bias · DE: ~3% · Concentrated in tech/crypto</div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding animate" style="animation-delay:.2s">
    <div class="finding-num">3</div>
    <div class="finding-title">Insider Evidence is Undervalued by Humans</div>
    <div class="finding-body">Doctors, police officers, farmers, lawyers, and social workers consistently produced the strongest arguments in both corpora — yet systematically undersold their professional observations as mere anecdotes. The AnecdoteDetector now rewards insider evidence (+0.35 bonus) and coaches users to claim their professional authority explicitly.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">Insider roles: avg 3.4/5 · Non-insider same topic: avg 2.7/5 · Δ +0.7</div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding animate" style="animation-delay:.3s">
    <div class="finding-num">4</div>
    <div class="finding-title">28+ Age Group Outperforms, 23-27 Underperforms</div>
    <div class="finding-body">Expected: monotonic improvement with age. Actual: 23-27 group scores lowest (2.66 EN). Hypothesis: this group is most likely to be in early career, overconfident, and arguing from professional identity rather than evidence. 28+ group has real-world failures that force more nuanced positioning. 18-22 group benefits from academic environment.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">18-22: 2.80 · 23-27: 2.66 · 28+: 3.15</div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding animate" style="animation-delay:.4s">
    <div class="finding-num">5</div>
    <div class="finding-title">Climate is the Weakest Topic Across Both Corpora</div>
    <div class="finding-body">Climate arguments averaged 2.56 in EN corpus — lowest of all 5 English topics. Paradox: climate has the most available empirical data, yet arguments are weakest. Cause: emotional framing prevents data citation. People feel strongly about climate but argue from emotion, not science. IntuitionTranslator impact: highest for climate topic.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">Climate avg: 2.56 · Crypto avg: 3.08 · Gap: −0.52</div>
  </div>

  <div class="finding animate" style="animation-delay:.5s">
    <div class="finding-num">6</div>
    <div class="finding-title">Strong Arguments Share One Pattern</div>
    <div class="finding-body">Every "strong" argument in both corpora (score ≥ 4.0) had exactly the same structure: (1) nuanced/partial position rather than absolute claim, (2) at least one external data point, (3) implicit or explicit acknowledgment of counterargument. No strong argument relied solely on personal experience. This is now the canonical "strong argument template" in the coaching system.</div>
    <div class="finding-stat">100% of strong args: nuance + data + counterarg · 0% personal-only</div>
  </div>

</div>

